nationally renowned. They sought to return to a simple form of monastic life, as set down in the Rule of St Benedict, and preferred rural locations "far from the haunts of men".But, as recent research has shown, they were by no means isolated from society but influenced, and were influenced by, the world around them; they moved with the times. This book seeks to explore the phenomenon that was the Cistercian Order, drawing on recent research from various disciplines to consider what it was that made the Cistercians distinctive and how they responded to developments. The book addresses current debates regarding the origins and evolution of the Order; discusses the key primary sources for knowledge; and covers architecture, administration, daily life, spirituality, the economy and the monks' ties with the world. Professor Janet Burton teaches at the School of Archaeology, History and Anthropology, University of Wales Trinity Saint David; Dr Julie Kerr is Honorary Research Fellow in the School of History, University of St Andrews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonasticism and religious ordersxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChrisianity.  aCistercian Order.  aanthropology.  aarchaeology.  acultural studies.  ahistory.  amedieval history.  amiddle ages.  areligion and classics.  areligious groups.  areligious history.  areligious studies.  areligious texts.  asociety.  asociology.1 aKerr, Julie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846159664?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/